summary:
The Security Council, 
Bearing in mind its primary responsibility for international peace and security, and underlining conflict prevention and resolution measures, 
Reaffirming resolutions on protection of civilians in armed conflict and UN personnel, 
Reaffirming commitment to the Charter of the United Nations, 
Reaffirming parties to an armed conflict bear primary responsibility to protect affected civilians, 
Recalling Geneva Conventions and Additional Protocols, 
Emphasizing existing prohibitions against attacks on civilians, 
Recalling States' obligation to search for and try persons alleged to have committed grave breaches, 
Drawing attention to justice and reconciliation mechanisms, 
Recognizing a comprehensive approach to protection of civilians, 
 Deeply concerned at violence against journalists in armed conflict, 
1. Condemns intentional attacks against journalists, media professionals and associated personnel; 
2. Considers journalists engaged in dangerous missions as civilians, respected and protected; 
3. Recalls media equipment and installations are civilian objects, not to be attacked or subject to reprisals; 
4. Reaffirms condemnation of incitements to violence, need to bring to justice those who incite; 
5. Demands all parties comply with international law related to protection of civilians, including journalists.
Here is a summarized version of the document:

The Security Council:

6. Urges States and parties to armed conflict to prevent violations of international humanitarian law against civilians, including journalists, media professionals and associated personnel;

7. Emphasizes States' responsibility to comply with international law to end impunity and prosecute those responsible for serious violations;

8. Urges parties to armed conflict to respect journalists', media professionals', and associated personnel's professional independence and rights as civilians;

9. Recalls that targeting civilians and committing systematic violations in armed conflict may constitute a threat to international peace and security and reaffirms readiness to consider such situations;

10. Invites States to consider becoming parties to the Additional Protocols I and II to the Geneva Conventions;

11. Affirms that it will address journalist protection in armed conflict under the agenda item "protection of civilians in armed conflict";
